04429nam a22005415i 9780226444079DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20092009ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264440797 a10.7208/97802264440792doi  a(DE-B1597)524682  a(OCoLC)489129425  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aTEC0000002bisacsh04a358.381 aKlotz, Lynn C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBreeding Bio Insecurity :bHow U.S. Biodefense Is Exporting Fear, Globalizing Risk, and Making Us All Less Secure /cEdward J. Sylvester, Lynn C. Klotz. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b4 halftones, 1 line drawing, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tCHAPTER ONE. Dangerous Crossing -- tCHAPTER TWO. A Future Bright and Dark -- tCHAPTER THREE. A Hawk Turns to Peace, Doves Go to War -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Devils We’ve Known -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Paranoia Begets Permissiveness -- tCHAPTER SIX. Dangerous Acquaintances -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. Who’s Minding the Store? -- tCHAPTER EIGHT. All Roads Must Lead to Public Health -- tCHAPTER NINE. Down to Grass Roots -- tCHAPTER TEN. Acting Globally -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the years since the 9/11 attacks—and the subsequent lethal anthrax letters—the United States has spent billions of dollars on measures to defend the population against the threat of biological weapons. But as Lynn C. Klotz and Edward J. Sylvester argue forcefully in Breeding Bio Insecurity, all that money and effort hasn’t made us any safer—in fact, it has made us more vulnerable. Breeding Bio Insecurity reveals the mistakes made to this point and lays out the necessary steps to set us on the path toward true biosecurity. The fundamental problem with the current approach, according to the authors, is the danger caused by the sheer size and secrecy of our biodefense effort. Thousands of scientists spread throughout hundreds of locations are now working with lethal bioweapons agents—but their inability to make their work public causes suspicion among our enemies and allies alike, even as the enormous number of laboratories greatly multiplies the inherent risk of deadly accidents or theft. Meanwhile, vital public health needs go unmet because of this new biodefense focus. True biosecurity, the authors argue, will require a multipronged effort based in an understanding of the complexity of the issue, guided by scientific ethics, and watched over by a vigilant citizenry attentive to the difference between fear mongering and true analysis of risk. An impassioned warning that never loses sight of political and scientific reality, Breeding Bio Insecurity is a crucial first step toward meeting the evolving threats of the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBiological warfare. 0aBiological weaponsxResearchxUnited States. 0aBiological weaponsxResearchzUnited States. 0aCommunicable diseasesxPrevention. 0aPublic healthxInternational cooperation. 7aTechnology & Engineering / General.2bisacsh1 aSylvester, Edward J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226444079423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226444079.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles